name: Ballard
blurb: Once you come here you can't leave, because no roads lead out of Ballard. Also, Scandinavian pride!
factsList: Has the Hiram Chittendon Locks which connect the Puget Sound to Lake Union
Known for Scandanavian people and festival
Notable Residents: Danny Stineback and Matt Wilson

name: Beacon Hill
factsList: Has the Pac Med building, formerly a marine hospital and former headquarters of Amazon.com
Has a light rail station
Home of the Beacon Food Forest, a large (15 acre) garden

name: Capitol Hill
blurb: 'This place is getting ruined by new transplants,'' say last year's crop of transplants
factsList: The most densely populated area in Seattle
Known as the home for Seattle's gay and lesbian population, or Seattle's 'gayborhood'
Notable Resident: Chris Perez

name: Central District
blurb: Seattle's best kept secret: A place you might want to live, with rent you might be able to afford! Makes you wonder what the catch is.
factsList: A very diverse residential neighborhood
Centrally located in Seattle (believe it or not)
Notable Residents: Stefanie Hansen, Bruce Lee, Jimi Hendrix, Quincy Jones

name: Delridge
blurb: I didn't even know this was a neighborhood until today. Rent is still probably stratospheric.
factsList: Borders the beautiful Duwamish River
Could be listed as part of West Seattle, but is not
Notable residents: Yes

name: Downtown
blurb: Hello? Does anyone live here? I'm stuck in the Chipotle on 3rd, send help...
factsList: Where the tall buildings are
Many new tall buildings are residential towers, which means some people actually live downtown now
Notable Resident: Claire Gatenby

name: Fremont
blurb: Fremont and Wallingford are where you go when you are a programmer who wishes they were cool and fun instead of an Amazon employee. Also, beer.
factsList: Summer Solstice Parade every year - famous for nude Solstice Cyclists
'The center of the universe'
Notable Residents: Peter Breen, Jeff Russell, and the Fremont Troll

name: Georgetown
blurb: Do you like airplanes, repurposed old brick buildings, and breweries? Have I got the place for you!
factsList: Right by Boeing Field
Known for Georgetown Brewery and Manny's Pale Ale
Notable person who has had a drink in Georgetown: Peter

name: Magnolia
blurb: Magnolia is where rich people live, and you know what that means. Look on the bright side - their multimillion mansions are likely to slide off the cliff into the Sound someday.
factsList: Magnolia's business district is called 'the Village'
Discovery Park is located here. This is the city's largest park
Magnolia Park overlooks Puget Sound, Mount Rainier, and the Seattle skyline

name: Northgate
blurb: Northgate is Seattle's shield against the danger of Shoreline. Haha sorry actually it's just a boring place with a really good bus route to downtown.
factsList: There's a mall.
North Seattle College is here (What, haven't heard of it?)
On the south end of Thornton Creek

name: Queen Anne
blurb: Queen Anne is where you go to have the best quads in the entire city. CLIMB THAT HILL, CITIZEN.
factsList: Sits on the highest named hill in Seattle
Populated by mostly unmarried young adults
Frasier (noted T.V. psychiatrist) lived in Queen Anne

name: Rainier
blurb: Seward Park is pretty cool. Also lots of people are afraid of being south of the domes, so take advantage of their ignorance!
factsList: One of the most culturally diverse neighborhoods in Seattle
Home of the Rainier Beach Vikings, a perennial high school basketball powerhouse
Seward Park is located in this area, a large peninsular park that juts out in to Lake Washington

name: South Lake Union
blurb: Watch out for 'Amazombies' who are ruining the neighborhood ... which used to be a pile of condemned warehouses.
factsList: The new tech center of Seattle
Has a streetcar that goes downtown. Transit name is 'SLUT'
Notable Developer: Paul Allen (Vulcan - is he?)

name: University District
blurb: The U-District has a million restaraunts and only two are good. Also a university, which means undergrads, which means loud parties and broken beer bottles.
factsList: The University of Washington is located here
University Ave is commonly known as 'the ave'
Notable Resident: Rashid Baset

name: Wedgwood
blurb: Wedgwood has a Top Pot. And some houses. Well, that's it.
factsList: Commonly misspelled as 'Wedgewood'
Wedgwood rock - 19 foot boulder on 28th Avenue NE and NE 72nd Street
Notable Residents: Jonathan Stern, Drew Ferris, and Aliza Pilisuk

name: West Seattle
blurb: And you thought Ballard was hard to get in and out of. Most West Seattle residents would be prefectly fine with WS magically turning into an island, because then you can't go there.
factsList: Original location of downtown Seattle, but the bay was too shallow', 'Has Alki Beach, a little bit of Southern California except for the rain', 'Notable Residents: Ivar Haglund, Eddie Vedder
